  "source": {
    "file_name": "Harrison's Principles of Internal Medicine, 20th edition",
    "content": "Polycythemia vera (PV) is a chronic myeloproliferative neoplasm characterized by increased red cell mass, often accompanied by leukocytosis and thrombocytosis. Clinical features include pruritus (especially after warm baths), erythromelalgia, headache, dizziness, and splenomegaly. Pruritus occurs in approximately 40% of patients and can be debilitating. It is typically exacerbated by warm water (aquagenic pruritus) and is thought to be mediated by histamine release from basophils and mast cells. Laboratory findings include elevated hemoglobin (>16.5 g/dL in men, >16.0 g/dL in women), hematocrit (>49% in men, >48% in women), leukocytosis, thrombocytosis, and elevated basophil count. The JAK2 V617F mutation is present in over 95% of patients. Treatment includes phlebotomy to maintain hematocrit <45%, cytoreductive therapy, and aspirin for thromboprophylaxis."
