  "source": {
    "file_name": "Harrison's Principles of Internal Medicine",
    "content": "For patients with typical symptoms of gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD) such as heartburn and regurgitation, an initial trial of empiric therapy with a proton pump inhibitor (PPI) is appropriate and cost-effective. A positive response to PPI therapy confirms the diagnosis of GERD in patients with typical symptoms. Upper gastrointestinal endoscopy is recommended for patients with alarm symptoms (dysphagia, odynophagia, weight loss, gastrointestinal bleeding), those with symptoms that persist despite appropriate therapy, and those at risk for Barrett's esophagus (e.g., chronic GERD symptoms, age >50 years, male sex, white race, central obesity). Ambulatory esophageal pH monitoring is the gold standard for documenting abnormal esophageal acid exposure and establishing a relationship between acid reflux and symptoms, but it is generally reserved for patients with refractory symptoms, atypical presentations, or before consideration of anti-reflux surgery."
