  "source": {
    "file_name": "Harrison's Principles of Internal Medicine",
    "content": "Acute STEMI is characterized by persistent ST-segment elevation on the ECG and release of biomarkers of myocardial necrosis, most notably troponin. The location of the ST-segment elevation indicates the region of infarction, with inferior MI typically showing elevation in leads II, III, and aVF. Initial management includes immediate administration of antiplatelet therapy (aspirin 162-325 mg and a P2Y12 inhibitor such as clopidogrel, prasugrel, or ticagrelor), anticoagulation (unfractionated heparin, enoxaparin, or bivalirudin), and consideration of reperfusion therapy. Primary percutaneous coronary intervention (PCI) is the preferred reperfusion strategy when it can be performed in a timely manner (within 90 minutes of first medical contact) by an experienced team."
